# Documentation Requirements

After generating or modifying features, task descriptions, or code, I will automatically document these changes comprehensively. This ensures knowledge transfer, maintainability, and clarity for all team members.

## Types of Documentation Required

### Daily Change Documentation

1. At the end of each working day, generate a daily status report with repomix:
   ```bash
   # Get today's date in YYYY-MM-DD format
   TODAY=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")
   
   # Get list of files changed today
   git diff --name-only $(git rev-list --since="00:00:00" --until="23:59:59" HEAD) HEAD > daily-changed-files.txt
   
   # Generate summary of only today's changed files
   repomix --include-from-file daily-changed-files.txt --style markdown --output docs/summaries/changes/daily-changes-${TODAY}.md
   ```

2. Update the [project-status.md](mdc:docs/project-status.md) file with:
   - Summary of the day's activities
   - Current status of active tasks
   - Blockers or issues discovered
   - Progress metrics (tasks completed, tests passing, etc.)
   - Link to the daily repomix summary

3. Create regular snapshots of critical project metrics:
   ```bash
   # Record current test coverage
   npm run test:coverage > docs/summaries/metrics/test-coverage-$(date +"%Y-%m-%d").txt
   
   # Record current performance metrics
   npm run benchmark > docs/summaries/metrics/performance-$(date +"%Y-%m-%d").txt
   ```

### Feature Documentation

After defining a new feature or updating an existing one:

1. Update the relevant feature section in [business.md](mdc:docs/business.md)
2. Include:
   - Business value and purpose
   - User stories or use cases
   - Integration points with existing features
   - Success metrics and acceptance criteria
   - Any constraints or limitations
3. Update [feature-status.md](mdc:docs/feature-status.md) with the current implementation status:
   - Percentage complete
   - In-progress items
   - Remaining work
   - Known issues
4. For significant features, generate a focused repomix summary of only the changed files:
   ```bash
   # Get list of files changed for this feature
   git diff --name-only $(git merge-base HEAD main) HEAD > feature-changed-files.txt
   
   # Generate summary of only the changed files
   FEATURE_NAME="feature-name"
   TODAY=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")
   repomix --include-from-file feature-changed-files.txt --style markdown --output docs/summaries/changes/${FEATURE_NAME}-changes-${TODAY}.md
   ```

### Task Documentation

After creating or modifying task descriptions:

1. Ensure the task is properly recorded in [sprint-current-tasks.md](mdc:tasks/sprint-current-tasks.md) with:
   - Clear metadata (type, priority, risk level)
   - Integration analysis details
   - Dependencies on other tasks
   - Acceptance criteria
   - Technical notes
2. Update [sprint-current-tasks.md](mdc:tasks/sprint-current-tasks.md) with the new task status
3. For completed tasks, generate a repomix summary of the files changed for the task:
   ```bash
   # For task-specific changes, use the task branch or commits
   TASK_ID="TASK-123"
   TODAY=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")
   git diff --name-only $(git rev-list --max-count=1 --grep="${TASK_ID}" HEAD) HEAD~1 > task-changed-files.txt
   
   # Generate summary of only the changed files for this task
   repomix --include-from-file task-changed-files.txt --style markdown --output docs/summaries/changes/${TASK_ID}-changes-${TODAY}.md
   ```
4. Create a task status visualization in [task-progress.md](mdc:docs/task-progress.md):
   ```markdown
   ## Task Progress (Updated: $(date +"%Y-%m-%d"))
   
   | Task ID | Status | Progress | Assignee | Blockers |
   |---------|--------|----------|----------|----------|
   | TASK-123| In Progress | 60% | @developer | None |
   ```

### Implementation Documentation

After generating or modifying code:

1. Add appropriate JSDoc comments to:
   - Classes, interfaces, and types
   - Public methods and functions
   - Complex algorithms or business logic
2. Update relevant technical documentation:
   - API documentation if endpoints changed
   - [technical.md](mdc:docs/technical.md) for significant technical decisions
   - Architecture diagrams in [architecture.mermaid](mdc:docs/architecture.mermaid) if structure changed
3. Add inline comments for complex sections or non-obvious decisions
4. Update task status in [sprint-current-tasks.md](mdc:tasks/sprint-current-tasks.md)
5. For major code changes or refactoring, generate a before/after repomix diff:
   ```bash
   # Today's date for filenames
   TODAY=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")
   COMPONENT="component-name"
   
   # Capture the before state of specific files that will be changed
   git show HEAD~1:path/to/file.ts > before-file.ts
   repomix --include "before-file.ts" --style markdown --output before-changes.md
   
   # Capture the after state
   repomix --include "path/to/file.ts" --style markdown --output after-changes.md
   
   # Combine into a change summary
   echo "# Before-After Changes" > docs/summaries/changes/refactor-${COMPONENT}-${TODAY}.md
   echo "## Before" >> docs/summaries/changes/refactor-${COMPONENT}-${TODAY}.md
   cat before-changes.md >> docs/summaries/changes/refactor-${COMPONENT}-${TODAY}.md
   echo "## After" >> docs/summaries/changes/refactor-${COMPONENT}-${TODAY}.md
   cat after-changes.md >> docs/summaries/changes/refactor-${COMPONENT}-${TODAY}.md
   ```
6. Update the [code-health.md](mdc:docs/code-health.md) document with:
   - Current technical debt items
   - Code metrics (complexity, duplication, etc.)
   - Areas needing refactoring
   - Recent improvements

### Sprint Completion Documentation

At the end of each sprint:

1. Generate a focused repomix summary of all changes made during the sprint:
   ```bash
   # Get sprint number and end date
   SPRINT_NUM="014"
   TODAY=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d")
   
   # Get list of files changed during the sprint period
   git diff --name-only $(git rev-list -1 --before="$(date -d '2 weeks ago' +'%Y-%m-%d')" HEAD) HEAD > sprint-changed-files.txt
   
   # Generate summary of only the sprint's changed files
   repomix --include-from-file sprint-changed-files.txt --style markdown --output docs/summaries/changes/sprint-${SPRINT_NUM}-changes-${TODAY}.md
   ```
2. Add a sprint cover note with:
   - Summary of completed stories/tasks
   - Key technical decisions made
   - Challenges encountered and solutions implemented
   - Items moved to future sprints
3. Update the [sprint-history.md](mdc:docs/sprint-history.md) document with:
   - Sprint velocity
   - Completion rate
   - Quality metrics
   - Key achievements
   - Lessons learned

## Project Status Tracking

The following documents must be kept current to track project status:

1. [project-status.md](mdc:docs/project-status.md) - Daily updates on project progress
2. [feature-status.md](mdc:docs/feature-status.md) - Status of all features under development
3. [task-progress.md](mdc:docs/task-progress.md) - Visual representation of task progress
4. [code-health.md](mdc:docs/code-health.md) - Technical debt and code quality metrics
5. [sprint-history.md](mdc:docs/sprint-history.md) - Historical sprint performance data
6. [risk-register.md](mdc:docs/risk-register.md) - Current project risks and mitigations

Each document should be updated after relevant changes and include:
- Last updated timestamp
- Current status indicators (green/yellow/red)
- Progress metrics
- Links to relevant repomix summaries

## Documentation Format Standards

1. **Consistency**: Follow established documentation patterns in existing files
2. **Clarity**: Write in clear, concise language
3. **Completeness**: Cover all significant aspects of the change
4. **Context**: Explain why changes were made, not just what changed
5. **References**: Link to related documentation or code where helpful
6. **Focus**: Include only changed code/content in repomix summaries to keep them concise and relevant
7. **Time-stamping**: Always include update timestamps in ISO format (YYYY-MM-DD)
8. **Status indicators**: Use consistent visual indicators for status (🟢 Green, 🟡 Yellow, 🔴 Red)

## Documentation Responsibilities

Different SCRUM roles have specific documentation responsibilities:

1. **Product Owner**: Business documentation, acceptance criteria, feature specifications, [feature-status.md](mdc:docs/feature-status.md)
2. **Scrum Master**: Sprint status, process documentation, change summary coordination, [sprint-history.md](mdc:docs/sprint-history.md)
3. **Solution Architect**: Architecture documentation, system design changes, technical decisions
4. **Technical Leader**: API documentation, code standards, identifying relevant changes to document, [code-health.md](mdc:docs/code-health.md)
5. **Developer**: Code-level documentation, identifying files changed by implementation, daily repomix summaries
6. **Test Leader**: Test plans, test cases, quality metrics, [risk-register.md](mdc:docs/risk-register.md)

## Documentation Checklist

Before considering any feature, task, or code change complete, I will:

- [ ] Create or update business documentation
- [ ] Create or update technical documentation
- [ ] Create or update task tracking documentation
- [ ] Add appropriate code-level documentation
- [ ] Verify documentation follows format standards
- [ ] Generate focused repomix summaries of only the changed content
- [ ] Update all relevant project status documents
- [ ] Share documentation with relevant team members

I will proactively mention documentation I've created or updated after completing major changes, and suggest additional documentation if needed for clarity. I will always focus on documenting only what has changed to keep documentation concise and relevant.